 to comment on individual departures among their more than 1,800 employees;=
 a rep noted that some of the international office closures had been long-p=
lanned.) Christie=E2=80=99s also reduced its staff, as often happens around=
 this time of year, but not at the same scale.

No matter what Sotheby=E2=80=99s is or isn=E2=80=99t saying, the belt-tight=
ening appears to be deep and wide and perhaps not coincidentally timed to t=
he arrival of the auction house=E2=80=99s new minority owner: Abu Dhabi=E2=
=80=99s ADQ sovereign wealth fund, which invested nearly $1 billion in Octo=
ber. The layoffs may not be a direct
condition of ADQ=E2=80=99s cash infusion, but the stipulations attached to =
the deal may have incentivized the restructuring=E2=80=94even if they also =
potentially threaten majority owner Patrick Drahi=E2=80=99s grip on the com=
pany.

So while much of the auction industry will be focused on the layoffs, the r=
eal question is what they indicate about Sotheby=E2=80=99s strategy going f=
orward. Drahi flirted with an I.P.O. in 2022, at a valuation of $5 billion,=
 but the rising-interest-rate environment shut that window before he could =
follow through. In many ways, the culling reflects a vision Drahi brought t=
o the company when he bought it five years ago: to make Sotheby=E2=80=99s b=
rand much larger than fine art.

$(ad3_title) ( https://ad.doubleclick.net/ddm/trackclk/N450204.4235921PUCK/=
B32594910.403585848;dc_trk_aid=3D602415983;dc_trk_cid=3D227021665;dc_lat=3D=
;dc_rdid=3D;tag_for_child_directed_treatment=3D;tfua=3D;ltd=3D;dc_tdv=3D1?u=
tm_campaign=3DDry+Powder+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%2812%2F11%2F24%29&utm_content=3DDry=
+Powder+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%2812%2F11%2F24%29&utm_medium=3Demail_action&utm_sour=
ce=3Dcustomer.io&utm_term=3Df6c60617da42abd12a )

When he took over, Drahi told a senior figure in the fine art division that=
 he really wasn=E2=80=99t interested in that business. He viewed the luxury=
 world as the company=E2=80=99s real potential for growth=E2=80=94classic c=
ar and real estate auction joint ventures, as well as handbags and jewelry,=
 which already drive meaningful business=E2=80=94even if fine art still dri=
ves the lion=E2=80=99s share of revenue.

As I=E2=80=99ve mentioned before, Sotheby=E2=80=99s recently invested heavi=
ly in new retail locations in the centers of Hong Kong and Paris. Its reloc=
ated New York flagship is set to open next year in the Breuer building, the=
 former home of the Whitney. The company has also relaunched its magazine i=
n a bid to expand on the sponsorships it already generates from brands=E2=
=80=94from Samsung to Cartier=E2=80=94that want to be associated with its a=
uctions and exhibitions. The immersive
train station experience that was built to promote Keith Haring=E2=80=99s s=
ubway drawings, which ended up bringing in $9.2 million, was paid for by Sa=
msung and featured their massive monitors showing trains pulling into the =
=E2=80=9Cstation.=E2=80=9D

A Leaner, Meaner Auction House

Sotheby=E2=80=99s decision to shrink the profitable company suggests the go=
al may be to generate more cash flow. One supporting clue lies in the docum=
ents filed with Companies House in the U.K. for Sotheby=E2=80=99s Holdings =
UK Limited, which reveal that the firm has a dual-class share structure. Th=
e preferred shares in the company pay an 11 percent dividend. If ADQ receiv=
ed those preferred shares for its investment, the payout would be an additi=
onal $100 million each year.

The additional dividend obviously presents a problem for Drahi, who ostensi=
bly does not want to rely solely on the potential rise in value of his equi=
ty in the company. (Sotheby=E2=80=99s C.E.O. Charlie Stewart told ( https:/=
/www.wsj.com/arts-culture/fine-art/art-market-sothebys-problems-6fa55009?ut=
m_campaign=3DDry+Powder+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%2812%2F11%2F24%29&utm_content=3DDry+=
Powder+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%2812%2F11%2F24%29&utm_medium=3Demail_action&utm_sourc=
e=3Dcustomer.io&utm_term=3Df6c60617da42abd12a ) The Wall Street Journal ear=
lier this year that none of the previous dividends have left its network of=
 holding companies. Others point out that Drahi focuses on tax management a=
nd nesting structures, which may explain why the ultimate holding company i=
s located in Luxembourg.) Management does have the option to make a payment=
 in kind if Sotheby=E2=80=99s lacks the cash to pay ADQ=E2=80=99S 11 percen=
t dividend. That would likely require the company to give ADQ additional sh=
ares, a move that could easily tip the
balance of ownership=E2=80=94and control=E2=80=94away from Drahi.

No one thinks Drahi will let go of the company easily, however. Thus, he ma=
y be buying time by cutting staff while hoping the art market rebounds. Sal=
es in Miami and in New York last month suggest ( https://puck.news/new-york=
-fall-art-auctions-review/?utm_campaign=3DDry+Powder+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%2812%2F=
11%2F24%29&utm_content=3DDry+Powder+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%2812%2F11%2F24%29&utm_me=
dium=3Demail_action&utm_source=3Dcustomer.io&utm_term=3Df6c60617da42abd12a =
) that the art market has turned a corner, or at least that it=E2=80=99s fo=
und the bottom, which means Sotheby=E2=80=99s could ride the next wave of t=
he cycle back to the point where Drahi can sell for the $5 billion valuatio=
n he once allegedly coveted, benefitting both himself and his partner. And =
from what I can tell, most of this week=E2=80=99s layoffs are in department=
s that are not likely to move the needle in the next wave.

We=E2=80=99re not hearing of many departures from contemporary art, for exa=
mple. And the way the auction business works, Sotheby=E2=80=99s thinning th=
e ranks of specialists doesn=E2=80=99t necessarily put it in a less competi=
tive position. Even after the growth of Phillips and the brightening prospe=
cts of Bonhams, the auction world remains a duopoly. On any big estate or c=
onsignment of property,
sellers will always want to get a competitive bid from the other side.

As we saw with the Sydell Miller estate, the power of Sotheby=E2=80=99s pla=
tform can be activated by a small, well-organized team working for the cons=
ignor. This has been done before. In 2010, Phillips partnered with Philippe=
 S=C3=A9galot to mount the $117 million Carte Blanche sale. S=C3=A9galot, a=
 former Christie=E2=80=99s head of contemporary art, did most of the work=
=E2=80=94assembling the property, cultivating the bidders, and even manning=
 the phones at the sale. For one night, he was a one-man contemporary art d=
epartment=E2=80=A6 and the sale was a rousing success. With the army of for=
mer auction house specialists now freelancing as art advisors and Sotheby=
=E2=80=99s sterling name, the company could easily run these sorts of asset=
-light auctions in its new sale rooms at the Breuer on Madison Avenue.

A year ago, Stewart attended Gagosian gallery=E2=80=99s show ( https://gago=
sian.com/exhibitions/2023/a-foreigner-called-picasso-curated-by-annie-cohen=
-solal-and-verane-tasseau/?utm_campaign=3DDry+Powder+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%2812%2F=
11%2F24%29&utm_content=3DDry+Powder+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%2812%2F11%2F24%29&utm_me=
dium=3Demail_action&utm_source=3Dcustomer.io&utm_term=3Df6c60617da42abd12a =
) of Picasso works, curated by writer Annie Cohen-Solal, and came away deep=
ly impressed and excited by the prospect of mounting his own museum-quality=
 shows. He wondered aloud to several of his staff what it would take, not s=
eeming to understand that all his team lacked were the funds=E2=80=94and ti=
me=E2=80=94to mount such a show, let alone several of them a year. A person=
 familiar with the planning of the Gagosian show told me that the insurance=
 fees on the eight-figure paintings on loan were not for the weak of heart.

But with a showcase like the Breuer building, where
many decades of museum shows generated lines around the block, Sotheby=E2=
=80=99s ought to have a major draw for its stable of corporate sponsors to =
offset the expense. In other words, there=E2=80=99s no obvious reason why S=
otheby=E2=80=99s cannot thrive with a reduced focus on fine art.

At this moment, the auction houses have never had such different business s=
trategies. The restructuring at Sotheby=E2=80=99s this month recognizes the=
ir diverging paths. That said, Sotheby=E2=80=99s new strategy will require =
the kind of flawless execution that proved elusive in Tuesday=E2=80=99s lay=
offs.

